  <section id="healthcare-system">
    <h2>Healthcare System Overview</h2>
    <p>
      Cyprus healthcare is adequate for most needs, with good private options supplementing the public system. For complex conditions, easy evacuation to major European centers provides access to world-class specialists.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Private hospitals</strong> in Cyprus include Apollonion Private Hospital (Nicosia), Ygia Polyclinic (Limassol), and Iasis Hospital (Paphos). These facilities provide good care for routine surgery, diagnostics, and most medical needs. Standards are reasonable, though not matching top UK or German hospitals.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>GESY public healthcare</strong> has improved significantly since 2019 launch. Wait times have decreased, facility quality is improving, and coverage is comprehensive. However, the system is still maturing—some specialists have limited availability, and complex cases may benefit from private or overseas care.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>English availability</strong> is excellent throughout Cypriot healthcare. Most doctors speak English, hospital administrative staff communicate in English, and patient documentation is available in English. This is one of Cyprus's key advantages for Anglophone retirees.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Evacuation destinations:</strong> When Cyprus facilities are insufficient, Athens (1 hour), Tel Aviv (45 minutes), and London (4.5 hours) provide world-class alternatives. International insurance evacuation coverage enables access to major European centers for cardiac surgery, oncology, neurosurgery, and complex procedures.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Prescription medications:</strong> Pharmacies are well-stocked with European medications. Many drugs are cheaper than in the UK. GESY covers prescriptions with small copays. Brand availability matches European standards—rarely issues finding needed medications.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="costs">
    <h2>Cost Planning</h2>
    <p>
      Cyprus offers good value for Mediterranean Europe—cheaper than France, Italy, or mainland Greece, while providing similar climate and lifestyle. Currency is Euro, providing stability for Euro-zone retirees.
    </p>
    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />
    <p>
      <strong>Total monthly budget</strong> for comfortable retirement with comprehensive health coverage typically ranges from €2,200-3,500 depending on location and lifestyle. Paphos comfortable retirement runs €2,400-3,200; Limassol is higher at €2,800-3,800; Larnaca offers value at €2,000-2,800.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Healthcare cost strategy:</strong> Full international insurance runs €350-750/month for seniors. Using GESY for routine care (minimal cost) plus international insurance for evacuation and complex care can reduce expenses while maintaining comprehensive protection. The right balance depends on health status.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Property considerations:</strong> Many retirees purchase property in Cyprus, which can reduce long-term housing costs compared to renting. The property market is established with good legal protections for foreign buyers. Purchase also supports permanent residence applications.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Sterling/Dollar income:</strong> Non-Euro income fluctuates against living costs. When GBP or USD strengthen against EUR, Cyprus becomes cheaper; when they weaken, costs rise. Maintaining some Euro savings provides buffer against unfavorable exchange movements.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="faqs">
    <h2>Common Questions</h2>

    <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 mt-6">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Can I rely on GESY for all healthcare needs?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">GESY provides comprehensive coverage for most conditions and is improving steadily. However, wait times for some specialists and complex procedures may still require private or overseas care. Many retirees use GESY plus private/international backup.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is Cyprus affected by the North Cyprus division?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">The Republic of Cyprus (south) functions as a normal EU country. North Cyprus is a separate entity not recognized internationally. Retiree communities are in the Republic. The division doesn't affect daily life for southern residents beyond occasional border curiosity.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How hot are Cyprus summers?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Very hot—July/August regularly exceeds 35°C (95°F) on the coast and 40°C (104°F) inland. Air conditioning is essential. Many retirees spend summers indoors midday or travel to cooler locations. Coastal breezes help, but expect intense heat June-September.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How large is the British expat community?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Substantial—estimated 40,000-60,000 British residents, concentrated in Paphos and surrounding areas. This creates established support networks, British-style pubs and restaurants, UK product availability, and healthcare providers experienced with British patients.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What changed for UK retirees after Brexit?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">UK citizens now need Category F permits like other non-EU nationals. EHIC cards no longer work (replaced by GHIC for visits only). S1 healthcare arrangements continue for those who established residence before Brexit. New retirees need private insurance.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is Cyprus safe?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Very safe—crime rates are among the lowest in Europe. Violent crime against foreigners is extremely rare. Petty theft exists in tourist areas but less than most European destinations. Cyprus consistently ranks as one of Europe's safest countries.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Plan Your Cyprus Retirement?"
    description="Get personalized quotes from insurers experienced with Cyprus retirement. Coverage that works locally and provides access to European specialists when needed."
    buttonText="Get Your Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />
</PageShell>
